          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/46744526-tabascosauce?shelf=rtc">rtc</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/46744526-tabascosauce?shelf=5-stars">5-stars</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1697144518" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7732681116521416245">This was a hysterical book and it made me laugh so many times! I loved it so much. Just the stories he has... it&apos;s not one of those books that has a point at the end or anything like that, but it&apos;s one that, if you&apos;re old enough, you notice -- one of those books where the characters change subtly so that by the end they&apos;ve gotten much more mature or changed some other way.<br/><br/>This was a really sweet book because you can see Joey understand his grandmother more. And that makes it sound like a dumb st</span>
  <span id="freeText7732681116521416245" style="display:none">This was a hysterical book and it made me laugh so many times! I loved it so much. Just the stories he has... it's not one of those books that has a point at the end or anything like that, but it's one that, if you're old enough, you notice -- one of those books where the characters change subtly so that by the end they've gotten much more mature or changed some other way.<br /><br />This was a really sweet book because you can see Joey understand his grandmother more. And that makes it sound like a dumb story but it really isn't because his grandmother is a hard-core tough army grandma but as the story moves along he, and you, both realize she's much, much deeper than that and he realizes that all of that is more like a mask and that she's trying her hardest to look out for and protect her grandchildren. But also give her grandchildren (Joey and Mary Alice) a really good time, away in the middle of nowhere (which is in stark contrast to their bustling Chicago home that they miss and also resent being sent away from).<br /><br />I love the book because it's sweet, sad, and hilarious. Richard Peck is a great author, he weaves the words so well that you think he's going one way - and he makes a complete u-turn. You think you understand the reason behind the character and find out they're up to something completely different. He's very simplistic, but you read between the lines and find something overwhelming and new, a hidden meaning that makes the book so much sweeter the older you get.<br /><br />This is a come-back-to-every-year kind of book that I will constantly be revisiting because I love it sm.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7732681116521416245" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


